WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:12.000
You want this to happen any more?

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:14.000
Sure.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:18.000
Today is Monday, July 25, 2011.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:25.000
My name is Joe Mosnier of the Southern Oral History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:36.000
I'm with our project, Video of the Fert John Bishop in Ithaca, New York, to do an oral history interview for the Civil Rights History Project,

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:44.000
which is a joint undertaking of Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:49.000
And we're delighted this morning to be with you, Ms. Cotton, and Ms. Dorothy Cotton.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:54.000
Thank you, I'm here to hear your Ithaca to spend some time talking about Civil Rights History.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:56.000
Thank you.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:10.000
Let me ask a very broad first question for some reflections I have read where you wrote that you wrote the follow and kind of thinking about the world that you came up in.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:15.000
You wrote from a very early age I felt like I was in the wrong place.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:17.000
Yes.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:19.000
It's not interesting.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:32.000
It is to me that the sense that I was in the wrong place was very, just sort of pervasive in my being.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:39.000
I couldn't put words on it at the time that I was feeling that as a youngster.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:57.000
But of course, as the years have moved on and I've moved on, I still reflect on it and have learned to have come clear on just that fact that I was supposed to be somewhere else.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:02.000
This is not my home community even.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:09.000
It was alien, alien to something in my very being.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:13.000
I don't know if you know something about that neighborhood.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:21.000
917 North Greenleaf Street in Goldsboro, North Carolina, North Carolina, where I was born.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:31.000
And outhouse in the backyard and people fighting and doing horrible things to each other.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:36.000
And that must have had something to do with it.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:42.000
Just the behavior of the people, not just the behavior.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:50.000
I don't know the way they were, the people in that neighborhood felt alien to me even as a child.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:53.000
And I think you lost your mother.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:57.000
My mother died when I was three years old.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:06.000
And of course, that was the depression and segregated southern town.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:15.000
What can you say to kind of frame the circumstances of your father's life after having lost his wife and the poor children's arrays?

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:18.000
What do I say about my father now?

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:30.000
And in these days, incidentally, my feeling about my father, my understanding of my father has evolved.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:37.000
When we were children, he was just the big guy.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:41.000
And he really wasn't big at all, skinny guy actually.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:47.000
But here's this big man raising full girls.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:53.000
And I know a lot, and I understand a great deal about him in retrospect.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:04:00.000
I know now that he went to, I think he said the third grade.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:05.000
And that's what stands out for me that he went to the third grade.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:12.000
Now, no matter did he just get to the third grade, they lived way out somewhere.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:18.000
I must research that place on somebody's farm, kind of a plantation kind of place.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:26.000
And his mother worked for a white family.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:30.000
It's interesting. I sort of choke on that kind of language now.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:34.000
I really don't even, one day, if I get, if I'm on the planet longer,

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:42.000
if I'm going to create a whole new genre of language with which to describe people,

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:46.000
because I'm really, I've jumped forward here.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:53.000
But it seems so just silly, ridiculous to me to continue to refer to people based on a color.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:57.000
As I said to a friend recently, well, she wasn't even a friend.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:01.000
I was doing a speech and I pointed to a woman sitting down front with a white blouse on.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:03.000
I said, they call you a white woman.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:09.000
But you know what, if you were the color of your blouse, I would call the ambulance and get you to a hospital.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:13.000
And my dress that I was wearing was black.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:18.000
My skin, Andrew Young Young calls it, I was a pecan tan.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:21.000
And so there's nothing old here.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:23.000
You know, it's not literal.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:27.000
But anyway, I sort of digress here.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:32.000
But I think about my father with a great deal of sadness now.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:41.000
And but also some anger, I can forgive to some degree the things that I,

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:49.000
well, the part of his behavior that makes me angry and that is still hurtful,

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:55.000
because I'm wise enough now to accept the fact that he didn't know any better.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:01.000
For example, the way he would discipline us, these four, I'm three.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:12.000
We were one two, less than one year old, three and four, the four of us, when my mother died.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:22.000
His notion of how you teach children and punish them was to take a strap and they were not soft blows.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:26.000
I can still feel anger about that.

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:33.000
But I have very mixed feelings about him because again, that's what was done to him.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:39.000
And I learned that very late in life that his mother would come home from taking care back to the color thing again.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:46.000
This white family and their children, his mother would come home late at night having left her children all alone.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:53.000
When she'd get home and my dad's older sister, Aunt Penny said this to me.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:56.000
I said, I'm Penny, how are you all punished?

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:04.000
Now, after I'm now reflecting on the ridiculousness and the pain of the way he punish does.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:12.000
And Penny, his sister said, well, when Mama would get home, she would find a reason to whip all of us with a switch.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:15.000
Sometimes they had to go get the switch.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:17.000
And it's even more horrible things than that.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:18.000
So I have such mixed feelings.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:32.000
Fast forward to the mixture now as I look back at my dad and as I do things that would be just beyond his imagination.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:39.000
I was in South Africa and I thought, oh, my dad could have had the experience of traveling to South Africa.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:42.000
If my dad, I mean, I've been in Chai, I've been in a lot of countries.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:45.000
If he could, my dad never even had an airplane ride.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:50.000
And even going to an airport was very special for him.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:53.000
Because that was not a part of his world.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:08:00.000
Even when we were all out of the house and one of my mother's sisters passed by and my dad was sitting on the porch,

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:08.000
and you're by himself and my aunt said, Claude, get in the car and come go with me up to Buffalo, New York.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:15.000
My dad, sitting on the porch and Goldsboro, North Carolina, jumped in my car.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:18.000
Had no plans to do that.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:25.000
Got up to Buffalo, New York, and set up his house keeping function there.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:33.000
So my, the sadness that I feel now is I'll give you a little anecdote and then I'll stop talking about him.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:40.000
We went, I flew there and to see him at some point.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:42.000
And after he'd been there a few years.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:48.000
And my dad, I said, can you want to go to the airport with us on a cousin who was living there.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.000
Drove us to the airport.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:54.000
And it was only five or six of us.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:59.000
And my dad, he was working at the Bethlehem Steel there.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:09.000
And when we finished eating in the airport, my dad pulled out his wallet and paid something like $42 for the five or six of us to eat.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:11.000
You could imagine that was some years ago.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:15.000
You wouldn't, you wouldn't eat for five or six people for that amount of money.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:18.000
One dinner would cost that now.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:21.000
And, and I remember much later, but that was very special for him.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:23.000
First of all, to be in the airport.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:34.000
And, and to pay that because my dad would have paid, would have had less than that amount of money for a week's work when we were children in Goldsboro, North Carolina, North Carolina, North Carolina.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:36.000
Working in this tobacco factory.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:38.000
Back to Goldsboro, North Carolina, North Carolina now in the tobacco factory.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:44.000
His job was to put tops on barrels where he'd have to use a hammer.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:46.000
And I'm not sure what it's called.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:49.000
It's a hammer on one side and an axe.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:54.000
Because he chopped a part of his finger off with that axe one day.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:57.000
Axe, hammer, I'm not, again, not sure what it's called.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:01.000
But, so he had that they did let him come home from work.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:05.000
And he got him to the hospital first and they sort of sold it back on what they did.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:07.000
But you could tell, he'd been injured.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:11.000
But back to the, now having made his way to Buffalo, New York.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:13.000
Being in the airport was very special.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:19.000
Another time when I had flown there, a cousin who lives there took me to the airport to get my ticket.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:21.000
And I was there to see him.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:25.000
When I got back home, he was sullen and quiet back to his house.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:28.000
And he was hurt because he didn't get to go to the airport.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.000
That was so special for him.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:33.000
Before I cry, I'm going to stop talking about him.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:37.000
It's a weird, it's just, it's very painful.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:44.000
The deprivation and what was so special to him.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:50.000
But, well, one way to speak of my dad was a real mixture.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:54.000
My own feeling is first of all, a real mixture of feelings.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:57.000
First, I can still be angry, feel angry.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:01.000
I feel the anger about the beatings for the, you break a dish.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:04.000
You know, he's got his belt off.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:13.000
But I can also remember, at Christmas time, he had a smile on his face when he could get off over a doll.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:17.000
And a T-set and our own box of fruit.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:19.000
And he was a shoe box.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:21.000
And he was so proud that he was able to do that.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:26.000
So, you can see, it was such a, oh, there must be a word for this.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:31.000
Such a mixture, both in terms of my own feelings and my own assessment of him.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:38.000
And his own feelings about his life and his work.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:47.000
But right now, in the year 2011, most of my feelings, sort of about my dad,

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:52.000
revolves around the deprivation of his life, his treatment.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:56.000
My dad was really nervous in front of white folks.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:00.000
And so, that's, it's a real mixture of my feelings about him.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:03.000
A kind of love for him.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:10.000
An understanding of the sort of mixed, that must be word for this as well,

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:14.000
feeling about his life and his relationship to us.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:18.000
It's positive, just a second.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:22.000
We'll go back on after a short break.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:28.000
Ms. Cotton, let me ask you about, I think in your life, as sometimes happens,

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:31.000
as folks come up, there was a teacher, a high school teacher in your place.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:32.000
Oh, yes.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:34.000
There was, it would be a very tremendous influence.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:40.000
And it helped you take a look step forward towards college and probably.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:46.000
I thought you were going to ask me what made me, there's a little story I want to tell you about,

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:52.000
I think I was around 10 years old, back on Greenleaf Street at North Goldsboro, North Carolina, North Carolina.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:58.000
When a little white boy was riding his bicycle down my block, kicking up dust,

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:02.000
because the pavement stopped at that, it got through the white section.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:07.000
And he was singing, you may be familiar with the song, deep in the heart of Texas,

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:10.000
where he was singing, deep in the heart of Nigger Town.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:15.000
I wanted to tell you that because I have never, ever forgotten that that made me angry.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:21.000
That little white boy was riding down my street singing that.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:24.000
Now, want to go back to high school?

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:30.000
Okay, that's what my high school days.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:40.000
Yes, I wish I could thank her in person, but Ms. Rosa Gray was my English teacher.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:56.000
Ms. Rosa Gray was not only the English teacher, she was responsible for the annual play for the high school.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:04.000
And I got the leading role in the high school play every single year.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:08.000
And I felt such a connection to her.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:16.000
But even before probably more than being aware and conscious of how special it was,

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:20.000
that she would name me this poor little girl from Greenleaf Street.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:25.000
But the teachers were poor too, compared to today.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:33.000
We had to, in the English classes, one day we had been required to memorize some poetry.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:39.000
And I don't remember what the poem was, but I do remember that as I stood before the class

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:46.000
and recited the poem, and as I headed back to my seat, she said very audibly,

00:14:46.000 --> 00:15:03.000
there's your ready girl till this day that phrase, that description just goes around and around in my consciousness.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:05.000
There's your ready girl.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:10.000
But I knew that, I think I'm going to cry.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:15.000
I knew that I never wanted to disappoint her.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:20.000
I wish there was something, not too much, that is the personal thing necessarily,

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:25.000
but was she something of a surrogate mother since you had lost your mother?

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:28.000
It's interesting that you say that.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:35.000
I never thought of her as a surrogate mother, but maybe she was a surrogate mother,

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:42.000
because I had no mother.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:45.000
She would...

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:46.000
This is...

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:49.000
Did you take it on that?

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:53.000
Yeah, let's just take a little break.

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:55.000
Okay, we're back after a short break.

00:15:55.000 --> 00:16:03.000
We're talking about Miss Gray.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:16.000
Of course, my sister would tease me a little bit, and when I talk about my fondness for her and my members of her,

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:22.000
excuse me, relationship with my English teacher, she's...

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:24.000
Are you sure you didn't love Miss Gray?

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:27.000
She was going to make sure you got lunch.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:28.000
But she was...

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:31.000
We all had a little laugh about that, because I was...

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:33.000
I wasn't feeling...

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:34.000
Anyway, I had...

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:37.000
Just some other feelings...

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:40.000
My sister made me laugh.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:45.000
But another example...

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:50.000
It's the notion of Miss Gray being a surrogate mother is what really got to me,

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:54.000
because I never thought of it that way, but I think that's true.

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:57.000
She...

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:09.000
There's the junior senior prom in high school, and when it was time to go to the junior senior prom,

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:12.000
my dad was not going to let me go.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:21.000
Miss Gray came to my house, sat on the porch, and those little houses along there,

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:26.000
those little three little row houses, and they're all torn down now.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:31.000
But the porch was high, so I wanted to get under the porch.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:35.000
My dad was sitting on the front porch, and my teacher, Miss Rosa Gray,

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:43.000
sat there, offered her a chair, and she was pleading with him to let me go to the junior senior prom.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:45.000
She said, she would...

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:46.000
Shaperone me?

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:50.000
I don't know if dad knew what the word Shaperone meant, bless his soul.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:54.000
But I think he said she would take care of me.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:57.000
But she was pleading with him to let me go.

00:17:57.000 --> 00:18:01.000
I mean, I'm her star pupil, and I can't go to the junior senior prom.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:06.000
And I remember that I, under the house, under the porch listening,

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:15.000
that I was really upset, and fast forward, believe it or not, 30 or 40 years later.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:20.000
It came clear to me why my dad said I could not go.

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:25.000
I'm sure my dad, as poor as he was, was a very proud man.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:33.000
He would not let me go to the junior senior prom, and that's what could be as dressed up as any other child.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:36.000
He had no money for that.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:43.000
He couldn't tell her that.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:52.000
He said, he said, I just, he wasn't ready for my girls to go to dances.

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:54.000
That's what he said.

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:56.000
He was going to talk proper for the teacher.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:01.000
I told you he went to the third grade and living out on that farm.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:07.000
Did you come up in the church?

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:09.000
Not really.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:18.000
My dad had a brief marriage to someone who was, I guess they married yet.

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:27.000
It's interesting that I never knew, but she was there as the stepmother, Mrs. and me.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:30.000
And I don't know what her name was before.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:36.000
I'm pretty sure they married, but I don't know anything about the ceremony or anything like that.

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:40.000
I don't know how many years, but it didn't last long.

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:48.000
And fast forward to a time when we all grown and married and living our various lives, my three sisters and I.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:56.000
And my dad, confessing to us that I wasn't loving Susie Mae.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:58.000
Those are his exact words.

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:02.000
I just brought her in there to help take care of you, young ones.

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:05.000
So that's why we had this stepmother for a while.

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:11.000
And the stepmother back to church was very much a church-going woman.

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:22.000
I remember once she was taking all four of us to church and there was a very threatening storm was pending, thunder and lightning.

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:27.000
And we were walking to the church and all four of us in tow with Mrs. and me.

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:29.000
And we always called them Mrs. and me.

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:37.000
And when she decided she needed to go back to the house because the lightning was so strong and fierce.

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:39.000
And we turned around and went back to the house.

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:44.000
And as she got to the house, she said, that won't, nothing but the devil.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:48.000
And so she was very much into church.

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:53.000
So she would put this on the devil and to keep her from going to church.

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:58.000
So that was a memory I have of Mrs. Mae.

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:03.000
I don't know when she left or how she left, but it wasn't long.

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:07.000
Fast forward, we reconnected with her like 40 or 50 years later.

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:10.000
And she died.

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:12.000
Now, but we reconnected with her.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:14.000
But she married.

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:19.000
And she married someone she called in Bishop somebody and was living in Florida.

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:21.000
And I saw her.

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:23.000
Yeah, Mrs. Mae.

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:25.000
She, yeah.

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:27.000
Okay, I got to short break.

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:28.000
Yeah.

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:34.000
I want to tell you, my dad, I never knew my dad to sit foot in the church except when his mother died.

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:42.000
As a matter of fact, I think my dad was anti church because I remember his saying,

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:45.000
we were, I guess, late teenagers.

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:50.000
Then somebody who was calling himself a preacher said, my dad said,

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:54.000
that ain't nothing but his racket.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:58.000
Maybe true folks, some of the folks who call themselves Reverend as well.

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:01.000
He's a way to make sure you have it income was my dad's thought.

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:03.000
Nothing but a racket.

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:06.000
But when he, I remember his going, of course, when his mother died,

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:08.000
and we were all there, of course.

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:14.000
And I remember his crying in the church bending over with his handkerchief to his face.

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:22.000
But other than that, my dad, but my mother, my actual blood mother,

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:24.000
my, I knew her father.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:26.000
He was a preacher.

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:31.000
And, and I, a tenorant preacher went from a small town to small town.

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:34.000
And I think he and my dad actually hated each other.

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:39.000
And my dad did confess, I'm not sure in what context, but he used the word

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:40.000
stole.

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:44.000
In other words, they looked, Maggie, my mother's name.

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:47.000
She was quite young.

00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:49.000
I'm not sure how old, but quite young when my dad had married her,

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:51.000
but they ran off and got married.

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:57.000
And I think that grandpa, her father, Mr. Reverend Seymour Pellum,

00:22:57.000 --> 00:23:03.000
and Reverend Seymour Pellum would come by the house.

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:09.000
We did call him grandpa, but he would, I could just tell that the energy wasn't right

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:13.000
in the house when grandpa stopped by.

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:17.000
Let me take you back to Miss Grandford just a moment.

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:18.000
Oh, yes.

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:21.000
As I understand, she would be, she was the part of the story.

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:25.000
She's in the story regarding your transition to Rolly to a ten shop.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:27.000
Yes.

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:32.000
Miss Gray, but we used to sing a song.

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:37.000
They used to sing people, church-going people in those days used to sing a song.

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:42.000
I know the Lord laid his hands on me, meaning that as a metaphor, you know,

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:46.000
that she laid her hands on me in a very special way, in other words.

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:54.000
Sort of took control of just really special events, or control of me in a special way.

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:59.000
But Miss Gray knew that college was not in the offing for me,

00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:05.000
but she called over to Shaw University when I was about to graduate from high school.

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:12.000
And talked to, I don't know, who, how, one got to go, who you talked to to get to go to college.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:21.000
But Miss Gray talked to someone there at Shaw, and I ended up being accepted as a student at Shaw University.

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:23.000
She had gotten two jobs for me.

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:27.000
One job was working in the dining hall.

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:34.000
The other job was cleaning the teacher's dormitory on the campus at Shaw University.

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:45.000
Eventually, well, eventually it makes it sound like a long time, but it wasn't very long before I was offered a job to be,

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:49.000
they didn't use the term, but a housekeeper in the president's residence.

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:53.000
For a very short time, I had three jobs working my way through college.

00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:55.000
My dad never gave me a dime.

00:24:55.000 --> 00:25:01.000
I don't blame him for that. He didn't have any money to, and probably didn't know what college was, not really.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:08.000
But so I was cleaning the teacher's dormitory, and eventually I was able to give up one of the jobs.

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:13.000
I think that was the one that I gave up, and still worked in the dining hall for a little while.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:18.000
But when I must have been a good worker and a good cleaner in the teacher's dormitory,

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:23.000
because I was invited to come and be a housekeeper for the president.

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:37.000
Dr. Robert Prentiss Daniel, and his wife Blanche Daniel, they had me coming over to instead of the teacher's dormitory to help take care of the president's residence.

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:46.000
Dr. and Dr. Robert Prentiss Daniel had no children, and I had a sense that ultimately,

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:51.000
in a way I was part daughter and part housekeeper.

00:25:51.000 --> 00:26:00.000
I worked very hard in that house, though, and it was a three-story house.

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:10.000
I stayed through graduation and getting married.

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:17.000
I felt like I was part daughter and part housekeeper.

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:23.000
The housekeeping part, or even being with them, the Daniels, the president of Shaw University.

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:29.000
It was not a happy relationship, so I'm taking care of the house.

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:35.000
Sometimes I get a feeling that they wanted me to act like a daughter.

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:41.000
That too was a very complicated relationship, because they weren't really nice to me.

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:47.000
I remember once I had the flu, and Dr. Robert Prentiss Daniel said, you can't just go to bed because you don't feel well.

00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:49.000
He even said that to me.

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:55.000
I got a check for a fast forward job in the library.

00:26:55.000 --> 00:26:59.000
That's really quite forehead, but I'm still living there.

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:06.000
Dr. Robert Prentiss Daniel opened the envelope. She wanted to see how much I was baking.

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:09.000
I have to tell you a little anecdote about my dad.

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:15.000
My dad came from Goldsboro, North Carolina while I was a student there at Shaw, and I'm now in the president's home.

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:21.000
My dad had never seen the flowers in the president's residence.

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:26.000
He said, what in the world does anybody want that flower shining like this for?

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:31.000
I was the one who polished those flowers and put the wax on the flowers or whatever for a while.

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:34.000
Then they had another fellow Robinson.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:36.000
This all I remember is Robinson.

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:41.000
It's never knew his first name would come and do some things in the house.

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:49.000
But I became sort of a, I think in a way they loved having me there, having no children of their own.

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:59.000
But at the same time, I don't have happy memories of being there, but it was helpful because they saw that.

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:06.000
I went to class. It took me at least six years to get my college degree.

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:17.000
I was in a class with a fellow, I think his name is Harris Sims, was a classmate of mine.

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:24.000
In a class, Shakespearean class, we both loved Shakespeare.

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:31.000
I remember that poem. I said in her class, I love reciting Shakespearian poetry.

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:38.000
And this fellow, Harris Sims sat next to me in this Shakespearian class studying Shakespeare.

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:44.000
And we used to walk down the hill, Harris Sims and I, to have a beverage.

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:48.000
We didn't have a campus center as they do on campuses now.

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:57.000
But there was a fellow who had a place for students to hang out and have refreshments just down the hill from Virginia State College.

00:28:57.000 --> 00:29:04.000
And sitting there one day of Sims said to me, I have a fellow I'd like you to meet.

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:08.000
And his name is George Cotton, fast forward, you can imagine.

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:20.000
So George Cotton, this, quite, must have been, George was at least ten years older than I, but that was not an issue then.

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:23.000
And I remember that they had this great big Buick.

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:30.000
And I had the sense that, anyway, George Cotton took a liken to me.

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:38.000
And I've read somewhere that people say I met George Cotton in college suggesting that he was a student as well.

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:44.000
But he was not. George never went to college. I don't know how far George Cotton went to school, but even.

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:51.000
But Cotton got to be quite heavy fast forward to a time when I actually said, actually I didn't say yes.

00:29:51.000 --> 00:30:00.000
He didn't ask me to marry him. He showed up one day with a ring and very correctly wanted to speak to Dr. Robert Prentiss Daniel.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:06.000
And I knew at that point what he was going to do. I didn't know he had a ring, but he wanted to ask for my hand.

00:30:06.000 --> 00:30:09.000
I wonder what George learned that.

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:13.000
I stood at the top of the stairs holding onto the banister.

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:21.000
And I heard George saying to Dr. Robert Prentiss Daniel that he wanted to marry me and he wanted their blessing.

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:28.000
And I remember that Dr. Robert Prentiss Daniel said to George, D'Artha is very ambitious.

00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:31.000
You sure you want this marriage.

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:36.000
And George said, yes sir.

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:43.000
George Cotton and I got married in the president's residence, this place where I scrubbed for the worst.

00:30:43.000 --> 00:30:47.000
Not scrubbed polished floors, then cooked, served meals.

00:30:47.000 --> 00:30:55.000
And again, I was a housekeeper and part daughter I used to say.

00:30:55.000 --> 00:31:01.000
But a very mixed, I could say a lot about the mixture of my energy.

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:05.000
One of those questions on that point and maybe this will illustrate that attention.

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:16.000
When Dr. Robert Prentiss Daniel made the transition from Shaw to Virginia State in 1950, and you moved and shifted your college to the moment up there.

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:18.000
Or you?

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:20.000
Yeah, I'm still at Shaw.

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:26.000
And what I was just saying was that Virginia State College at that point.

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:31.000
When I moved, when Dr. Robert Prentiss Daniel was offered the president's of Virginia State College,

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:35.000
I guess I was a really good house cleaner because they wanted me to go with them.

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:40.000
Yeah, I was ahead of the story because all of it, what I was just talking about happened at Virginia State College.

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:44.000
I was at Shaw probably no more than one year, one school year.

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:50.000
And went to Virginia State College because Dr. Robert Prentiss Daniel became president of Virginia State College.

00:31:50.000 --> 00:32:00.000
And this is where, and this is where I mentioned the classmate, Sims, and I meant, anyway, I'm sorry.

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:02.000
No, no, I was just curious.

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:09.000
Yeah, but that was interesting because I was thinking about being on the campus, but I need to, which campus am I talking about now?

00:32:09.000 --> 00:32:11.000
When Dr. Robert Prentiss Daniel got the offer?

00:32:11.000 --> 00:32:18.000
Of course, it would be in Petersburg where you would be drawn after college more directly into early movement activities.

00:32:18.000 --> 00:32:22.000
Well, I got to Virginia State College.

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:34.000
And that Virginia State College, again, that's where this Sims, and I were in the Shakespearian class, that was not as short, was at Virginia State College.

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:38.000
And George Cotton lived there in Pita's bird.

00:32:38.000 --> 00:32:47.000
And when I said yes, I would marry him and even had the ring, I think he gave me the ring that later on that evening.

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:54.000
And there was a little wedding right there in the house.

00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:55.000
I meant.

00:32:55.000 --> 00:32:57.000
That's a policy for Christus.

00:32:57.000 --> 00:32:59.000
Do you not have a turn to...

00:32:59.000 --> 00:33:01.000
Okay, we're back down.

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:02.000
That's a little break.

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:03.000
For the telephone.

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:05.000
So did we get married here?

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:06.000
We were very...

00:33:06.000 --> 00:33:09.000
We were talking about how you would be drawn into...

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:16.000
I want to tell you about a little boy, because I consider this the beginning.

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:23.000
Not so much drawn into the movement, but a particular consciousness was evolving.

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:26.000
And back to my childhood, when...

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:32.000
Did I tell you about the little boy driving down the sidewalks, seeing deep in the heart of Nigger Town?

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:42.000
Okay, I know that a consciousness about the wrongness of this system was that opened it up for me.

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:49.000
Okay, fast-forward to Virginia State College.

00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:58.000
And when I became active in a church in...

00:33:58.000 --> 00:34:00.000
Pita's bird, Virginia.

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:02.000
I got to sit his right here.

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:10.000
And the Reverend Wyatt Tee Walker was pastor of this church.

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:21.000
And I'm not sure why I started going there, except that Wyatt Tee Walker was also the regional head of the NAACP.

00:34:21.000 --> 00:34:23.000
And also the other...

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:33.000
I think it seems like all of the organizations really related were very close to Congress or racial equality and at the time.

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:37.000
And I think I was drawn to that church because of his...

00:34:37.000 --> 00:34:39.000
He was also a really good preacher.

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:42.000
And he also was a very handsome guy.

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:53.000
We used to tease each other because my house became the house after getting really involved with all of his extracurricular activities and also very active in the church.

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:57.000
Even on programs sometimes still doing poetry.

00:34:57.000 --> 00:35:00.000
I remember reading poetry from the balcony in the church.

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:04.000
And it was just really fun hanging out with Reverend Walker.

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:16.000
So being active, he's running the NAACP and becoming concerned that Black folk could not use the public library.

00:35:16.000 --> 00:35:25.000
He took a real initiative there around that library discrimination in the library.

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:35.000
And I thought, just imagine we can't use the public library and yet they, white folks, call us ignorant.

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:41.000
And I felt that very strongly now as...

00:35:41.000 --> 00:35:47.000
I'm not sure exactly what year it was, but that will be easy to find.

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:49.000
I may remember it in just a moment here.

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:55.000
But Reverend Walker asked me to...

00:35:55.000 --> 00:35:59.000
He saw my interest if I would help the...

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:12.000
In this organizing and training of children, especially younger people, because he wanted us to put a picket line in front of the library and ultimately in front of the Woolworth's store downtown.

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:24.000
But we started with the library and I found a letter as a matter of fact because I became secretary to him, secretary of the NAACP.

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:35.000
And I had to therefore just really kind of be with him regularly in that work and handling the communication.

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:43.000
So I was trained, ended up training youngsters in the church to walk with picket signs and how...

00:36:43.000 --> 00:36:52.000
And I had heard something of non-violence and we invited this young preacher from Montgomery, Alabama, Martin Luther King to come up to Petersburg, Virginia.

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:58.000
To speak for work because we now started having what we call mass meetings as well in Petersburg.

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:05.000
Reverend Walker had met Martin at a conference at Virginia Union University in Richmond, Virginia.

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:16.000
I remember he was telling me that. He had met him and now Reverend Walker is very much interested in what was going on in Montgomery, Alabama, the Montgomery Bus Boycott.

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:23.000
And invited this little preacher from Montgomery to come up and speak for us.

00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:37.000
Reverend Dr. Martin Luther King did just that because in cities where there was a protest activity and it seemed to be just springing up all over the place, this protest activity.

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:46.000
And so now everybody had a mass meeting. We call them mass meetings. This is for some reason. Well, I think maybe it's obvious.

00:37:46.000 --> 00:37:54.000
The mass meeting interested the meetings and all those cities and definitely in Petersburg, whatever where.

00:37:54.000 --> 00:38:02.000
People were interested in coming to the mass meetings because they wanted to hear what was going on in town.

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:11.000
So they started coming to the mass meetings and when everybody now, massive numbers of people were hearing about the Montgomery Bus Boycott and Rosa Parks.

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:18.000
And when he came up to speak for us, Dr. King, I was on the program.

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:32.000
You know, when Black folks have programs with God, music and dancing and poetry and singing and everybody's involved, I used to try to tell the students at Cornell University University when we pay all this money for a speaker to come.

00:38:32.000 --> 00:38:38.000
And they just have the speaker walk up and very coldly give his speech and walk off with $10,000.

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:42.000
Put some flowers on the table. Let's have some music. Let's do something.

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:49.000
So maybe that's a cultural difference, I don't know. But I did poetry back to my love of poetry again.

00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:59.000
I remember that we had dinner at the parsonage at Reverend Walker's house.

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:10.000
And the young women's parish club was the organized group of women in the church that was hosting and planned the dinner and we were serving the dinner.

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:28.000
And I was moving around the table from the kitchen to the table. And Dr. King wanted to know, I can see him now sitting at the end of this quite long table in the parsonage at Reverend Walker's house.

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:38.000
And he wanted to meet that young lady who said the poem on the program earlier that night.

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:48.000
Somehow the meal I think was after the program. And so I was identified. It was Dorothy Cotton who said the poem on the program.

00:39:48.000 --> 00:39:57.000
And he wanted to meet me and I stood by the head of the table where he was sitting or maybe it was the foot of the table, one end of the table.

00:39:57.000 --> 00:40:12.000
And I told him about the point. And we had a nice little chat. He was a user to me, very unassuming little guy, you know, rather short of statue.

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:22.000
As Coretta used to say, she was not impressed when she saw him in terms of statue or anything like that. But there was still something very impressive about him.

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:31.000
And I enjoyed standing there chatting with him at the table because we were the young women's Parish Club. We were serving the meal.

00:40:31.000 --> 00:40:40.000
While he was there in Petersburg, he was very much interested in what we would, our protest activity, picketing in front of the library.

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:52.000
And I had run the workshops, knew nothing substantive about non-violence. But I knew that you were not supposed to fight or hit anybody back. Very simplistic at that time.

00:40:52.000 --> 00:41:01.000
But I'm helping the youngsters prepare to walk in front of the dime store, Woolworth's store, and in front of the library.

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:17.000
But apparently before Dr. King left Petersburg, he asked Reverend Walker to move to Atlanta, Georgia. And while she walked, Revan Walker said, I will move to Atlanta, Georgia to work with you as you are developing this organization, the Southern Christian Leadership Conference.

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:30.000
I'll move there and work with you. If I can take the two people who helped me here, that was a fellow named James R. Wood and me. If he could take us.

00:41:30.000 --> 00:41:43.000
And so, while I Walker raised the subject with me and would I be interested in going, and I said to my husband, George Cotton, I told him this door. And I said, I'd like to go down and help them out for about three months.

00:41:43.000 --> 00:41:59.000
And George was very quiet, didn't say very much. I'm not sure what he felt. I can summarize. Now, many, many, many years later, the pain it must have been for him because I went. George Cotton, my husband, drove me to Atlanta, Georgia.

00:41:59.000 --> 00:42:20.000
And Revan Walker was in the process of moving and I got to Atlanta, Georgia and to stay my three months that I promised my husband. And George, as I said, drove me there. And would come down once or twice, he came down in the early months.

00:42:20.000 --> 00:42:34.000
But I stayed 23 years. That the movement became my life once I, but that's how I got there. His coming up to visit Dr. King, coming to visit us in Petersburg. And then my going going with to work with Reverend Walker.

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:41.000
And ultimately becoming, I ended up being a director of education for SCLC.

00:42:41.000 --> 00:43:03.000
Exactly. We'll turn to that. Just once I, one quick little question about the timing in Petersburg. It's not crucial. We could look this up easily enough. But you're, I believe the protest activity that you and in Petersburg and other folks carried forward out of the church in the Petersburg Improvement Association. That, that began in 59, I think.

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:08.000
Do you remember? I think the Greensboro sit-in, February 1, 1960.

00:43:08.000 --> 00:43:22.000
Oh, I'd have to look at the dates. It would be at the moment. That's okay. But I think you guys were even, you know, picketing in front of the Greensboro City. And then of course, after that, things really exploded.

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:29.000
I was not picketing in Greensboro. No, no, but you mean the movement, some movement people. Oh, yeah.

00:43:29.000 --> 00:43:34.000
Oh, no, your, your pickets in front of the library and in front of wallboards.

00:43:34.000 --> 00:43:37.000
Yeah, okay. Okay. Were those before?

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:44.000
Oh, I see what you, I'll see what you're saying. I'd have to, I'd have to research that. It's not a crucial thing. Yeah, I'd have to look at it.

00:43:44.000 --> 00:43:47.000
But interesting question that you raised. Now I'm curious about it.

00:43:47.000 --> 00:44:01.000
Tell me about, tell me about what you found when you arrived in Atlanta, Georgia to join this organization called the Southern Fisheries Conference, which had only a very, very small step.

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:16.000
Well, it was just a warning, as they say. The Southern Christian Leadership Conference was, had not yet come into the big importance organization that we know it as we know it or came to know it.

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:21.000
I don't want to talk about today. That's another story.

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:30.000
But when I arrived, I remember, first I had to find a place to live in George Cotton, having driven me down my husband.

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:39.000
We stayed at a motel. I'm not sure which one for several days. And then George headed back to Petersburg, Virginia, where we were living.

00:44:39.000 --> 00:44:50.000
And I remember focusing on a place to live. And I can talk about that. Ended up well.

00:44:50.000 --> 00:44:56.000
I'm not sure which should come first, but maybe it doesn't matter.

00:44:56.000 --> 00:45:07.000
Your question specifically was what I found when I got there. I found three or four people in an office on Albert Avenue.

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:18.000
And at least three people. And I only remember three people being there that I talk about.

00:45:18.000 --> 00:45:30.000
Young woman, Lily Hunter. I can't believe I'm blocking on an elevator.

00:45:30.000 --> 00:45:40.000
And the girl, woman named her, her name is Brown. Those were the three people in the office.

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:48.000
As I remember, I'm not sure when her name came on, but I think I found her there that she was working there.

00:45:48.000 --> 00:45:55.000
But definitely, Ms. Ella Baker. And Lily Hunter had moved up from Montgomery as I understand.

00:45:55.000 --> 00:46:01.000
I don't know where she is. I don't know if she's in custody. Are you familiar with her name? Okay.

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:06.000
Lily Hunter. Those were the three people there.

00:46:06.000 --> 00:46:14.000
And of course, I'm this sort of wide eye. Youngster never traveled, having traveled much or lived in another city.

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:23.000
And I feel like I was exploring possibilities for my life. I feel like I was on a track to something different and new.

00:46:23.000 --> 00:46:29.000
I didn't know what it was. I didn't know what the organization was. So I had a lot to learn.

00:46:29.000 --> 00:46:44.000
But I have to include in my transitioning into Atlanta, Georgia looking for a place to live and ended up staying for a few months with Dora McDonald, who became Dora.

00:46:44.000 --> 00:46:50.000
Oh, well, it was Dora working for him. I have to get the chronology straight here.

00:46:50.000 --> 00:46:58.000
I lived with Dora's with Dora for a few months. I lived with, you know, I got a room in a house.

00:46:58.000 --> 00:47:03.000
I will think of the woman's name quite. We call her everybody called her L and L. Doley.

00:47:03.000 --> 00:47:09.000
But I had a room in her house in an elderly woman's house.

00:47:09.000 --> 00:47:14.000
I'll think of the name. I'm going to have to call you up and give you the name.

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:19.000
So anyway, so it was a room there and ultimately a room in Dora's house.

00:47:19.000 --> 00:47:23.000
I need to remember when Dora came on board. Dora must have already been there.

00:47:23.000 --> 00:47:32.000
But I met her and she had a Dora had a house. And I ended up staying with Dora for a short time, I think just several months.

00:47:32.000 --> 00:47:41.000
And you changed that to stay with Dora McDonald, who became Dr. King's Secretary, and then staying with the elderly woman.

00:47:41.000 --> 00:47:44.000
I hate saying elderly woman. I'll tell your name in a minute.

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:51.000
Thank you. My goodness. Oh dear. Now I'll have to take you to the White House too.

00:47:51.000 --> 00:47:58.000
Yeah, Ms. Mosley, that's right. Stay with Ms. Mosley a longer. She was, how could I forget that?

00:47:58.000 --> 00:48:00.000
Does anybody else forget?

00:48:00.000 --> 00:48:04.000
No, we all forget. But the porch is a story. Yeah, it was Ms. Mosley.

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:09.000
Very recently. Right. I stayed with her. And I became quite at home there, but I just had a room.

00:48:09.000 --> 00:48:14.000
But she made me feel very welcome. There were no children there and her son and his wife lived there.

00:48:14.000 --> 00:48:23.000
So I lived with Ms. Mosley until I, again, see me just entering into life in Atlanta, Georgia.

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:29.000
And eventually, not too long. Maybe I stayed with Ms. Mosley. I know she had how long maybe a year.

00:48:29.000 --> 00:48:36.000
I got myself on an apartment and was shopping around for quite a while and found this apartment.

00:48:36.000 --> 00:48:45.000
And by that time, of course, I'm enmeshing myself now in this growing organization, F-C-L-C.

00:48:45.000 --> 00:48:53.000
And just kind of learning the ropes. Another thing I remember moving into Atlanta, Georgia was during these weeks when I'm looking for a place to live.

00:48:53.000 --> 00:48:58.000
I remember that first, as soon as George left, I was walking through an area.

00:48:58.000 --> 00:49:02.000
And I remember fellow snatching my pocketbook, which I'd never got back, incidentally.

00:49:02.000 --> 00:49:12.000
And now here, I'm this new, never traveled much at all. And having this happen, exploring, staying in these two or three different places, you know,

00:49:12.000 --> 00:49:21.000
roaming with people. But Dora became, was Dr. King's secretary. I'm not sure when she became his secretary,

00:49:21.000 --> 00:49:23.000
but I did have a room in her house for a while.

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:26.000
But she had been at Moorhouse?

00:49:26.000 --> 00:49:31.000
I'm not sure. Would she have been, she might have worked there.

00:49:31.000 --> 00:49:34.000
I thought she had come over from Moorhouse.

00:49:34.000 --> 00:49:39.000
Maybe from Morehouse And was a very accomplished professional secretary with the E.C.

00:49:39.000 --> 00:49:47.000
She was. She was. I have written that Dr. King said Dora could be secretary to the president of the United States.

00:49:47.000 --> 00:49:56.000
And I wrote in my book manuscript that I'm doing. I hope that Dr. King told her that, that she could have been.

00:49:56.000 --> 00:50:02.000
One thing we haven't mentioned as we're kind of coming through the late 50s and the early 60s, is that you would also just earn a master's degree.

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:04.000
So you would ride with a master's degree?

00:50:04.000 --> 00:50:07.000
Yeah, I was doing a number of things, kind of simultaneously here.

00:50:07.000 --> 00:50:19.000
What happened was, now, this is after the marriage, my marriage to George Codden, this was, and this was before going to SLC.

00:50:19.000 --> 00:50:26.000
But yes, I went up to, I just, again, I knew that I was hungry for something and that something was on the horizon for me.

00:50:26.000 --> 00:50:30.000
I can only put that in words now. But I said to my husband, I wanted to work on a master's degree.

00:50:31.000 --> 00:50:41.000
And then I, so I went up to Boston, to Boston University for one summer, I think it was first.

00:50:41.000 --> 00:50:49.000
And I came back home and then I realized I wanted to go back and really seriously pursue the degree, which I did.

00:50:49.000 --> 00:50:53.000
I came home for a semester then went back, decided to stay and finish it.

00:50:54.000 --> 00:51:03.000
So I did get the master's degree. As a matter of fact, that's one day I got clear about, because it was in the summer of 1960.

00:51:03.000 --> 00:51:15.000
And I knew that I was questioning whether I would stay and march in Capungown in the commencement exercise to get this master's degree.

00:51:16.000 --> 00:51:29.000
And decided that I would indeed do that, because it had been quite a struggle and working it into my, into my, working it into my, my schedule of things that were kind of cooking for me, things that were on my mind.

00:51:29.000 --> 00:51:43.000
And in the summer of 1960, I, that's when I said to my husband, I want to go, I want to accept this invitation from Reverend Walker to go with him and the invitation from Dr. King to go to Atlanta, Georgia.

00:51:43.000 --> 00:51:48.000
So I went to Atlanta, Georgia a few days after I got the degree at Boston University.

00:51:48.000 --> 00:52:00.000
In an organization that, as you say, a warning in those, in those months, in the early 60s, such a small group of people, your original title on arrival, I think, was Director of Education.

00:52:00.000 --> 00:52:09.000
Not originally. I was working as an administrator assistant to Reverend Walker. I went down there. And that's because we didn't know what we were going to be.

00:52:09.000 --> 00:52:15.000
And I didn't even know that we were going to need, that we were going to have this education program. So I was working as Reverend Walker.

00:52:15.000 --> 00:52:23.000
I remember saying to him, one day he was piling so much stuff on my desk and, and how, how, I'm a good type, fast typist. And we didn't have computers in those days.

00:52:23.000 --> 00:52:33.000
So I'm sitting there typing and, and that one day I said, God, you expect me to finish this. This is so much, Reverend Walker on my desk. But I was his administrative assistant.

00:52:33.000 --> 00:52:46.000
One, one story that stands out in my mind, or one event that stands out. For me is, one day, Dr. King pulled a chair up in front of my desk, because I'm sitting there with stuff all piled around my desk.

00:52:46.000 --> 00:52:56.000
And, and it was almost like it was interviewing me and asking me a lot of questions about my life and family and school and whatever, just chatting.

00:52:56.000 --> 00:53:06.000
And, short, they after that, he asked me if I would go over to a place called Highlander Folk School, short, they after that.

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:14.000
And that's when I really kind of put two and two together and realized that I was really sort of being interviewed as I, some eyes.

00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:30.000
And I'd have to tell you the whole story of Highlander, but I don't really need to do that except that Highlander was in the throes of being closed down because they had all sorts of phony charges leveled at them.

00:53:30.000 --> 00:53:45.000
And, and I think that was the first time I've ever seen this communist school. And there was a, you may have heard of this billboard on the side of the road with Mrs. Eleanor Roosevelt and Dr. King on the same roadside sign.

00:53:45.000 --> 00:53:57.000
And, and somewhere in the caption was these have been to that communist school. Interestingly, one woman at, at Myles Horton, who founded Highlander Folk School.

00:53:57.000 --> 00:54:09.000
And, and the imperial service after he died, one woman said, told this story. And she said, we owe a big laugh at Myles' funeral. They wouldn't have done communism from rheumatism.

00:54:09.000 --> 00:54:23.000
Because, they're calling the school a communist school. And then, because, you know, Myles Horton was, we had like folk and white folk meeting together when that was just not the thing to do in those days.

00:54:23.000 --> 00:54:44.000
But I was asked to go over to Highlander. And because Dr. King and company must have seen the handwriting on the wall. The state was just, they were just taught it all the time and charge and just had many charges leveled against them, including selling whiskey.

00:54:44.000 --> 00:54:54.000
And I understand that they had served beer at, at an event there, the Highlander folk school. And the Highlander folk school is another, you know, a whole story.

00:54:54.000 --> 00:55:02.000
But when Dr. King asked me if I would go over there to just meet the people and check out the school to get to know something of the school, I did just that.

00:55:02.000 --> 00:55:17.000
So now I'm moving away from being an administrative person to Reverend Whitey Walker. I went to Highlander and I met this woman and Septima (Poinsette) Clark. And because Septima (Poinsette) Clark was working there at the Highlander folk school.

00:55:17.000 --> 00:55:28.000
There's an interesting story about how she got to work there. I'll see if I can summarize this. But Septima (Poinsette) Clark had met Esau Jenkins.

00:55:28.000 --> 00:55:48.000
Esau Jenkins was a man who lived on the John's Island, you know, the Sea Islands off the coast of Charleston. And Issa had, I think I've been told more than one, but he used to drive a school, old school bus he had acquired from the islands to the mainland of Charleston.

00:55:48.000 --> 00:56:00.000
And taking people back and forth to work is very enterprising man. And he would take a little break for the telephone.

00:56:00.000 --> 00:56:05.000
There you go. Okay, we're back after a short break. Talk about Esau Jenkins.

00:56:05.000 --> 00:56:24.000
Yes, I, when I did go over to Highlander and I met Septima (Poinsette) Clark there. Septima (Poinsette) Clark had met Esau Jenkins who had a little transportation service bringing people, taking people back and forth to work from John's Island to Charleston back and forth.

00:56:24.000 --> 00:56:37.000
And John's Island stands out in my mind some of the other islands, Ward, Maloe, the other islands off the coast of Charleston, ultimately were involved.

00:56:37.000 --> 00:56:50.000
But I really want to tell you about, I'd like to share the fact that Esau Jenkins experienced an event, he didn't see it.

00:56:50.000 --> 00:57:02.000
Well, let me tell you what the event was. A white man shot a black young boy. And the white man shot the boy because the boy accidentally ran over the man's dog.

00:57:02.000 --> 00:57:15.000
So he just killed the boy. And understand the dog really ran out in front of the truck, I think it was. And so, but the white man killed the boy, this black boy.

00:57:15.000 --> 00:57:29.000
And the people predominantly African American and literally African American, you can still hear the well of language they call it spoken around the island there in those days.

00:57:29.000 --> 00:57:42.000
And Issa realized that something was wrong with that picture because the people of John's Island didn't rise up and righteous indignation when this man decided to just shoot the boy and nothing happened.

00:57:42.000 --> 00:57:58.000
And Issa was smart enough to know that they didn't didn't protest this killing because the boy, because the people of, they didn't protest the killing because the people on the island had no political power.

00:57:58.000 --> 00:58:21.000
What I've just said really is the germ of the citizenship education program that ultimately came my job because what happened was Issa started helping people on, on his old, his bus as he drove them back and forth to work, understand why it was important for them to register to vote and talking to them about political power.

00:58:21.000 --> 00:58:37.000
And it's amazing that Issa, well, since this, knew this, understood this and its relationship to an event like that. And the Septima Clark said, Esau Jenkins had a third grade education, but a PhD mind.

00:58:37.000 --> 00:58:52.000
And I like to quote that because it must be true he could see that the people having no political power and the people on the island also were predominantly functionally illiterate on the island there.

00:58:52.000 --> 00:59:13.000
But Issa met Septima Clark. Her story also relates to my going to, as you'll see, in the sense that septum had been fired from the Charleston school, school system. She had been a teacher, but she was fired because she would not say whether or not she was a member of the NAACP or not.

00:59:13.000 --> 00:59:21.000
And they met Esau Jenkins and septum of met actually had a conference at the Highlander folk school.

00:59:21.000 --> 00:59:39.000
So we can just sort of actually, I guess, is a fast forward a little bit here to a time when the citizenship education program that is helping functionally illiterate black folk, African American people understand their political power.

00:59:39.000 --> 00:59:53.000
It just grew like tops. It was in septum and Issa met each other there at the Highlander folk school. Issa was wanting people to discover their political power and literacy training was a major part of that.

00:59:53.000 --> 01:00:01.000
And then meeting this teacher who loved to, there's a photograph of Septima Clark holding an elderly gentleman's hand helping him learn to do cursive writing.

01:00:01.000 --> 01:00:13.000
Because in those days, one had to do cursive writing to sign your name, and which was probably a trick too to just to keep black folk from registering to vote.

01:00:13.000 --> 01:00:25.000
So my being there meeting septum of who now moved came over from Charleston to work there at the Highlander folk school in Issa and her and septum of working together now.

01:00:25.000 --> 01:00:37.000
I just want to tell you that for Highlander was fighting for its very life in the courts at this time, and they lost that battle. In other words, the state confiscated that property.

01:00:37.000 --> 01:00:52.000
Beautiful property there in the Cumberland Mountains. And because they lost that property, so Highlander in terms of location was kind of in limbo for a while, maybe one way to speak about that.

01:00:52.000 --> 01:01:04.000
But ultimately they got a new property, which is just beautiful in the mountains in that area. I should be able to describe it more directly.

01:01:04.000 --> 01:01:21.000
And can I have written about it in my book manuscript. But now that they were in the time between the time from actually losing the Highlander folk school, the people who were funding these workshops now that septum and use septum of work.

01:01:21.000 --> 01:01:29.000
So septum could help them learn to read and write. And is always talking the political aspect of it.

01:01:29.000 --> 01:01:39.000
Everybody wanted to make sure this training continued. SCLC now, my organization, Dr. King's organization inherited the organization.

01:01:39.000 --> 01:01:51.000
The Marshall Field Foundation who gave the major funds to the Highlander school to run do this training, helping these black folk learn to reading, write enough so they could register and vote.

01:01:51.000 --> 01:02:00.000
They were interested in keeping this training program going for these people. And eventually, not eventually.

01:02:00.000 --> 01:02:12.000
It didn't take them long to decide they would give those funds to SCLC to run this citizenship education program. And I was asked to become the director of citizenship education program.

01:02:12.000 --> 01:02:27.000
Thanks to Andrew Young Young, who also Andrew Young Young had secured through the good offices of his church, the congregational church, a facility there in Macintosh, Georgia.

01:02:27.000 --> 01:02:41.000
And we would hold workshops there. And now, Andrew Young, September and I would travel the south, recruiting people to come into the five day residence of workshop.

01:02:41.000 --> 01:02:54.000
Because what happened after we could probably point to a number of horrible events now around the south. But we knew that we could do more with this training program than just help people learn to read and write.

01:02:54.000 --> 01:03:06.000
We could expand it to helping them understand their political rights. They could understand that their rights as a citizen, what that all meant.

01:03:06.000 --> 01:03:21.000
Because Andrew Young had a connection with the congregational church, being a congregational minister, we found this, the Dorchester Center at McIntosh, Georgia, and appropriated the national church owned.

01:03:21.000 --> 01:03:34.000
So we started having workshops there. But now, in vision, September, Maclark, Andrew Young Young, and I traveling the south. And we would target places where protest activity was springing up everywhere.

01:03:34.000 --> 01:03:49.000
And we would go into places that were just kind of hot beds of activity now. And we would tell people we have this five day residence of workshop. And we would invite them to come to Dorchester Center.

01:03:49.000 --> 01:03:58.000
And they would have a wonderful experience because we know you're fighting for your rights here. And we will help you discover ways to do that.

01:03:58.000 --> 01:04:16.000
I remember sitting in someone's living room, actually in North Virginia. And my friend, Eunice Minnis, and Albert Minnis, the husband, hosted me because I had met Eunice Menis a teacher when I was doing my student teaching before I graduated from college.

01:04:16.000 --> 01:04:26.000
And Eunice invited me to her house, and her husband sat there. And so Al said, you made a wonderful talk, Dorothy.

01:04:26.000 --> 01:04:35.000
But if you're going to tell these people, invite these people to come to your five day workshop. And because when I finished telling them, then I said, and we'll pay your way.

01:04:35.000 --> 01:04:47.000
He said, you did that backwards. And now, Albert Menis described himself as a junk man because he really did sell parts of old cars. His wife was a teacher.

01:04:47.000 --> 01:05:03.000
But he would, and it was interesting. He had, I think, had a lot of fun calling himself a junk man. This junk man told me how to do my selling of the notion of the invitation to come away with us to Dorchester Center.

01:05:03.000 --> 01:05:16.000
And so tell them first that you're going to pay that way because while you're talking, they're sitting there thinking, I can't afford to go anywhere. I can't take a trip. If they know you're going to pay that way up front.

01:05:16.000 --> 01:05:27.000
So I thought, here's this junk man telling me with the master's degree, how to recruit people, and how to make my little speech to invite them to come. So anyway, I have a lot of fun with that.

01:05:27.000 --> 01:05:32.000
Tell me about Andrew Young. Tell me about Septima (Poinsette) Clark. Tell me about Bernie Sravitz.

01:05:32.000 --> 01:05:45.000
Well, Septima (Poinsette) Clark was, incidentally, Septima (Poinsette) Clark and especially Septima (Poinsette) Clark and Andrew Young and I used to, well, we would, the three of us in a car.

01:05:45.000 --> 01:05:57.000
And I think people would sometimes think we were mother, son, and daughter. Septima (Poinsette) Clark being the elder, you know, in the car. But we would go from city to city, but we would target one place and we would go.

01:05:57.000 --> 01:06:06.000
Septima (Poinsette) Clark, because there was a spirit about her that was just a warm and she was sort of the grandmother type.

01:06:06.000 --> 01:06:19.000
I have an image of what that is. I don't know if people hearing that coming from me now would necessarily know, but people know grand grand motherly in the sense of what grandmothers used to look like.

01:06:19.000 --> 01:06:27.000
But now when I see somebody and they tell me they have grandmother, they have grandchildren. I think they look like they're 29. You are a grandmother.

01:06:27.000 --> 01:06:48.000
But in a way, the grandmother type had a different connotation in those days. You know, you were older, you walked slower and you didn't dance. But grandmothers, I know now, I have a friend who's a grandmother. She lays down a mean, she's a grandmother.

01:06:48.000 --> 01:07:06.000
But so we were in the car and Septima (Poinsette) Clark still focused on this, this is her part of the teaching that we would do. Septima (Poinsette) Clark focused on the handwriting, because in a lot of places you had to do, one had to know cursive writing in order to register.

01:07:06.000 --> 01:07:21.000
I think it was just a trick to actually exclude black folk. And there were massive numbers of African American people across the Southland especially and other places too. But we were focusing across the South.

01:07:21.000 --> 01:07:35.000
But if they could do block, or make block letters, that wouldn't do. You have to do cursive writing. Septima (Poinsette) Clark was very good at that. There's a photograph of Septima (Poinsette) Clark holding an elderly gentleman's hand helping him learn to do cursive writing.

01:07:35.000 --> 01:07:52.000
Andrew Young and I also had a particular focus. We came to play a particular role in the five day residence of workshops. Now inviting folk to come to the Dorchester Academy.

01:07:52.000 --> 01:08:19.000
And I would plan the five day sessions. And Andrew Young would get into the politics. I remember one session. The main session, Andrew Young did was actually pushing people to understand. As we all did that, but why voting was important. And even I used to name the session when I would write out the outline of the week's work. Why one vote matters. And Andrew Young would tell the story.

01:08:19.000 --> 01:08:35.000
I'm forgetting which president won because one vote made a difference. And so your vote counts. Andrew Young wanted to emphasize the fact that one vote matters. And I remember so vividly and is doing that session.

01:08:35.000 --> 01:08:59.000
And I remember that I was in the process of bringing Robinson also was in the urging people to understand the politics as I was as well. But I laid out the five day sessions. And we were I got people to work with the people who came with it has to be understood that these were sometimes functionally illiterate people, but who are active in their communities.

01:08:59.000 --> 01:09:26.000
And I got invited to come. And but we also had people who were sort of itinerary preachers or preachers like anyway, my dad has an interesting description. I think I mentioned earlier about who some of these preachers were. But they would also come to workshops. And I had to in the workshop help them understand what it meant to have a dialogue going between all the people and not just beat up on people because you were the preacher.

01:09:26.000 --> 01:09:36.000
Because especially those the black communities from which a lot of the people came were if you call yourself a preacher, people felt like they had to be quiet if the preacher spoke.

01:09:36.000 --> 01:09:49.000
But sometimes they knew more than the preacher. I don't mean to to integrate you know to but but the preachers had to learn what it meant what the ways people learn, for example.

01:09:49.000 --> 01:09:58.000
And that people needed to feel encouraged and and they didn't need to feel that they had to shut up because somebody who called himself a preacher was speaking.

01:09:58.000 --> 01:10:02.000
But also there were there were also good men of the cloth.

01:10:02.000 --> 01:10:08.000
Let me ask a couple questions about the for more detail about the about the five day training.

01:10:08.000 --> 01:10:21.000
I read that that you made a very careful point to rather than say to lecture from the front of the room a set of specific lessons we want to understand right to start conversation.

01:10:21.000 --> 01:10:22.000
Of course.

01:10:22.000 --> 01:10:33.000
So out of the group's conversation would develop a more focused understanding of the things that the attendees wanted to know.

01:10:33.000 --> 01:10:44.000
I have a very interesting still is interesting to me. I don't know if this would be maybe it's included in what people call the socratic method of teaching.

